review_blob:
When my family left England, they should have brought a case of this over. Granted they left in 1682, but Im still faulting their lack of foresight. 

Great big caramel nose, taste and finish. A lovely palate of dried fruits, maybe raisin. Lovely.
Really quite smooth for an IPA. Spot on sweetness. I was expecting scorched earth, but this was downright silky.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Double Wide I.P.A.

review_blob: Simple, a bit sweet, straight forward, not unpleasant. Perhaps too watery? Light for a bock.
Quick on the tongue. It was preceded by a Belhaven Stout, so my palate might have been overpowered. Worth a second try.
Really? 95? It taste like coca-cola. Reminds me of South African/ Australian wines that sweeten their vintages before bottling. Perhaps Im a Luddite, but I was not impressed.
Its nice! And the carriage glass its served in is ace. If you fancy strong Belgian ales youll love it. If you dont, why do you have a rate beer account in the first place? Exactly.
Im not sure why, but Im crushing on Scottish Ales at the moment. Damn you, William Wallace! Seriously though, fine malts with a flavorful finish.
Such a nice IPA. I havent enjoyed one this much from start to finish since AleSmith. And thats saying a lot.
Belhaven: superior stout. Guinness:superior marketing. This is fantastic, will a truly developed palate. Im honestly surprised its not rating higher.

Cant believe it took me so long to try this, but it was worth the wait. Had it on tap no less at Opals Marina the other night. Great, very balanced, with wonderful drinkability. Everything works; smell, taste and color. Very, very good.

OoooOOooOO. This is nice. I tried it at Opals last weekend and was really impressed. I liked the citrus/malt mix, and picked up on apricot, nectarine, and caramel. Went and bought a four pack at Grapevine. Nice job. You sold me.

beer_brewer_name: North By Northwest Restaurant and Brewery
review_blob: So, are they marketing this as the new Tu Helen Bock, because whats up with the logo? Tried a sample, and then filled up my growler, only to get home and have the buyers remorse that I didnt get the Saison 600. Its ok, sweet and lightly wheaty. Ill try it again.
Yowza. Instant favorite. Very dark with a fair amout of cragy head. Rich, very rich...Scrooge McDuck rich. Great range of flavor: nutty, sweet, cocca and coffee. Delicious. I love it.

Im not even sure why I thought this would be a good combo, although I could put maple syrup on just about anything and be happy--so go fiqure. Very thin and watery texture, pretty weak composition. Am I the only one that tastes more vanilla extract than maple syrup? Glad I bought a single 12oz...probably wont try again.
Really nice color. Deep brown with little head. Smells of coffee and cocca. Taste is muted raisin, plenty of malt, and some sweet caramel. An excellent brown ale...top notch.
Caught my attention by the label (sucker for any take on the English flag--not the Union Jack). Pretty clear, medium head. Dry throughout & fizzy. Pretty dang bitter. Dang.
Bottle. Nice smokey brown color. Smells malty, with a nose of nut and brown sugar. Taste is on the sweet side...pleasing.

The packaging is the best so far of their annual special releases...but the taste falls short. Im drinking it right now, and the nutty aroma of roasted almonds is better than the dull, watery taste. Ill probably keep an unopened bottle, because, hey, Im not really going to miss it. And, per commercial deScription..."darkest lager possible"...wha?

Picked it up on a whim as Whole Foods, without knowing what the rating is. I sense allot of acidity, and it obscures the flavor. Not really all that familiar with scotch ales, but this isnt bad. A bit sweet; curiously complex. Overall, its ok.
Nice copper hue. Medium boddied with flavors of pine, cedar, caramel, roasted almond. Nice.
beer_name: Lost Coast Indica India Pale Ale

review_blob: Hmmm. A quandry. I can appreciate how much craftsmanship is behind this, but honestly, I didnt find it that enjoyable to drink. Very yeasty and sweet, with a hint of watered down bourbon. Goes down warm and spicy. A little raisin, brown sugar and caramel. I love that AleSmith makes a product like this, but now that Ive tried it, I probably wont rush to get another.

Ive got to say, this is really worth the effort to track down, especially if its not distributed to your state. Hazy pour with nice amounts of billowy head. Like many IPAs the piney scent is there, but not overpowering. Before I drank this I downed a NXNW Kodiak IPA, which I had aged for little over a month, and the piney scent of that was much stronger. The AleSmith was a great combination of grapefruit, nectarine, orange cream, and malty hop. The finish isnt long enough when it comes to something as satisfying in the mouth as this. Didnt pick up too much Vanilla--like the label says, but it was no biggie--this was truly great. Now one of my favorites.

beer_brewer_name: North By Northwest Restaurant and Brewery
review_blob: Pale yellow pour. Super thin head. Very watery texture with a very fragile malt flavor. Short finish. Eh, not my favorite from here.

Batch 4. Sweet Jesus. This is the only beer Ive ever gotten a buzz from just by drinking one. Its like you were driving a raisin truck that slid on molasses and then slammed into a spice mill that had walls made of brown sugar. Head is thick and rocky enough to inspire mountaineers to take notice. Also, the head is seriously powerful stuff, and gives a great indication of the range youll experience once you actually drink the liquid itself. The spectrum is amazing: brown sugar, caramel, candied fruit, vanilla, raisin, honey and apricot. Im pretty proud it only took me 45 minutes to finish it and I never once slipped into a diabetic coma. Yes, Virginia...it is a beast.
beer_name: Avery The Beast Grand Cru Ale

beer_brewer_name: North By Northwest Restaurant and Brewery
review_blob: Hazy yellow color served in a tulip glass. Dense head. Smells of muted citrus and spice. Very sweet  at first with a wonderful, almost warm bitterness. I could taste orange, grapefruit, spice, and nectarines. Very smooth, easy to drink, especially in triplicate. Very good.
Wow. Powerful. Very piney. Hops through the roof.  Citrus smell is a mix of grapefruit and lemon peel(?) Somewhat chewy. Very nice.

Draught @ Draught House Pub, Austin. Had this on my birthday, which beats the hell out of having a cake. Great story behind it. Very dark brown pour. Peppery, fruity and sweet. I thought I tatsted candied fruit or nuts. Nice consistancy-medium finish. Really good stuff.

I had this right after the Hop Gold, and I really didnt notice a huge difference. A wallflower; this really could be mistaken as something more generic--not a house brew.  My buddy was drinking this and we compared the two side by side, and they were nearly the same color with similar aromas, but this had a weaker hop texture. Pretty watery, a bit bitter, with a medium dry finish. [Shrug]
Hazy golden color. Has a malty hop aroma with weak citrus undertones. Not bad--a bit watery.

beer_brewer_name: North By Northwest Restaurant and Brewery
review_blob: Boy, I got pretty excited as the waitress walked across the room toward me with this on her tray---it looked great from afar in its tulip glass. Cloudy golden color. Thin white head. Looks almost like a hefeweizen, not a typically fizzy Belgian strong ale. Smells very sweet. Has a delicate aroma of spice and maybe pear(?) I was really surprised because I expected the alcoholic content to affect the taste in the way a Rochefort or St. Bernardus does, but this was absolutely sublime. Excellent!  Dare I say it-but it reminded me of an amalgam between a creamy wheat beer and a Belgian white ale. Very impressive--really good stuff!
beer_name: North By Northwest Guldenbiere (2005, 2007 and later)

beer_brewer_name: North By Northwest Restaurant and Brewery
review_blob: Draught. Copper color with a thick-white head. Looking into the glass, it has a unique appearance; like something hearty, or organic with substance. Smell is fresh and fruity. The exact fruit is hard to pinpoint, but maybe an apricot. Taste is sweet--not overly hoppy, which surprised me given this is an IPA. Substantial malt flavor. Very mellow character; somewhat subdued. Gradual bitter finish. Very drinkable.

Bottle. Very unique (and VERY strong) wood smell--like bamboo or maybe cedar. Im not sure of the hop variety used, but I can say that Ive never had an IPA with this exact flavor. Super sweet, very syrupy.
beer_name: Avery The Maharaja Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle. Dark, hazy amber color looks great. Smells hoppy-with aromas of bread, citrus (lemon) and spice. Taste is sweet, incredibly balanced Bitter finish makes me salavate...for more. Excellent.

On tap @ Fish City Grill, Austin. Light amber color with small amount of off-white head. My experience was that it was an explosion of hops up front, but not a lot of range within the composition, and the flavor faded quickly--short finish. Tasty, but seemed somewhat one dimensional.

On Tap @ Fish City Grill, Austin. Typical hazy orange. Smells like lemon and citrus. Taste is crisp, somewhat acidic, and not as sweet as German Hefeweizens. Seems like its missing a key ingredient to make it complete.

Bottle. Medium amber color. Smells fizzy, with aromas of fruit, chocolate and caramel. Taste reminds me of a mix between Belgian strong ale, barley wine, and coca-cola. Malty, with a noticeable absence of hops. Alcohol content is very detectable. Interesting, and easily the best product Independence puts out.

Tap @ Draught House Pub, Austin. Disgusting--although Im pretty sure the rancid taste was the pubs fault for serving it (I suspect) in a dirty glass. Smelled like the zoo. Since Ive heard such great things about it I will try it again and then re-rate.

Poured black. Had a pretty thick brown head. Looked creamy, but was a tad watery. Chocolate taste was pretty weak, although I did just finish a Youngs Double Choc. Stout before ordering this. Average.

Draught @ Anchor restaurant inside San Francisco Airport. Yellow, poured with a light head (waiters fault). Smelled sweet-like honey and citrus fruit. I was parched and this quenced my thirst, although it was pretty watery. Not bad.
Draught @ the brewery. Jeez, this was good. Extremely well composed for an imperial/double IPA. Very bitter and rich; made me salivate while drinking it. Best beer I had all night there. Great stuff.

Draught @ the brewery. Smells like roasted malts and pine. Tastes like the hop concentration was spot on compared to the RRs IPA. Could detect a grapfruit and caramel taste. Although a little on the watery side, still pretty impressive.

Woo Hoo; first rating! Draught @ the brewery.  Rich amber color. Smells of granny smith apples, plums and raisin. Taste is a combo between a beligian strong ale and apple cider. Metallic aftertaste was not expected. Finish is bitter...like sour apple. Interesting, but one was enough.
Draught @ the brewery. Gold. Smells of apricots & citrus fruit. Extremely easy to drink. Lemon zest finish. Very very good.
Draught @ the brewery. Smoky amber color. Very strong hop flavor, but balanced. I could pick up on the citrus ovetones pretty easily. Dry, long finish.
Straight out of the bottle. Smells and tastes sweet-but artificial, like it has some weird amalgam of additives. Hmmm, not too much bitterness, just a moderate hoppy taste. Pretty average.
beer_name: Widmer Brothers Drop Top Amber Ale

review_blob: Bottle. Pours reddish/amber. Carbonation seems light; it isnt. Smells like apples. Taste is sweet, like caramel with a touch of sour apple.  Quick finish. Delightful.

Bottle. Pours a beautiful amber color.  Smells earthy with a strong aroma of wood--like cedar. Taste is expectedly hoppy for something called maximus. Spicy in the mouth. Taste is strong, dry, and has a medium/long finish. I cant shake the wood taste. Jeeez.
Left over from the holiday mix-pack. Pours black. Smells sweet, a bit like black coffee. Toasty--dry finish. Nice.

Bottle. Pours black. Very little head. Smells like a chilled coffee. At first, I taste some nuttiness, and then it turns to a creamy vanilla-like melted vanilla bean ice cream. Finish is abrupt. No texture; watery, and composition is very light in the mouth. Seems like this has two stages: nutty, then vanillaand then its gone. Easy to drink, though.
Ive had it several times over the years. Weak body, watery, very bland. About as Irish as my Italian grandmas meatballs.
